hypothesis: Explicit dispatch scores increase domain coverage uniformity by ≥15%
method: Parse DOMEX lanes from SWARM-LANES.md + ARCHIVE. Split at S302 (dispatch optimizer introduced). Compare Gini coefficient and domain coverage ratio across eras.

result.verdict: NEGATIVE — dispatch scores concentrate work, not spread it

interpretation: Explicit pricing (dispatch scores) trades breadth for depth. The optimizer directs work to high-scoring domains, improving merge rate (quality) but reducing coverage (diversity). This is the classic exploration-exploitation tradeoff. The swarm's dispatch mechanism is an exploitation amplifier, not a diversity mechanism.
recommendation: To improve coverage uniformity: (1) add dormant-domain bonus in dispatch scoring (already exists as +3.0 but insufficient), (2) enforce minimum per-domain DOMEX cadence (at least 1 lane per 20 sessions per domain), (3) separate 'exploration budget' that dispatches to lowest-coverage domains regardless of score.
caveats: Lane ID parsing has noise (abbreviation codes not fully mapped)
Pre-dispatch era includes many S186 expert-generator lanes (batch creation inflates count)
Post-dispatch era is shorter (50 sessions vs 301 sessions)
